Glibc isn't singling out assembly language programs for special treatment. 
Pure C programs work the same way, and this is why the main program protion of a C prgoram is called the main function (they are very literal on naming)

The standard C library code calls it with a "CALL" instruction, and it returns control to the standard C library code by executing a "RET" instruction. 

	Overview: 

		1) A procedure must perserve the values of the EBX, ESP, EBP, ESI, and EDI 32-bit registers. The contents of all other general-purpose registers may be altered at will. 

		2) A procedure's return value is returned in EAX if it is a value 32 bits in size or smaller. Sixty-four-bit integer values are returned in EDX and EAX, with the low 32 bits in EAX and the high 32 bits in EDX. FLoating-point return values are returned at the top of the floating-point stack. Strings, structures, and other data items larger than 32 bits in size are returned by reference; tha is the procedure returns a 32-bit pointer to them in EAX. 

		3) Parameters passed to procedures are pushed onto the stack in "reverse" order (think of the stack eating it from right to left given the direction of the def). Given that C function "MyFunc(foo, bar, bas)", "bas" is pushed onto the stack first, "bar" second, and "foo" last. 

		4) Procedures themsleves do not remove parameters from the stack. The caller must d that after the procedure returns, either by popping the procedures off the stack or by adding an offset to the stack pointer ESP. 

